)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.9, compare 7.208, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 8.12 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; καθ᾽ ἡσυχίαν at <b>leisure</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 1224, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.48, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to διὰ σπουδῆς, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 6.2.28 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μετὰ.. ἡσυχίας <b>quietly</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 205 (_anapaest meter_). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> with Verbs, <br /><Level4><b>__4.a</b></Level4> ἡσυχίαν ἄγειν keep <b>quiet</b>, be <b>at peace</b> or <b>at rest</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.66, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 38a, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 6.2, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 4.1, etc.; περὶ μὲν τῶν ἄλλων ἡ. ἦγον, ὑπὲρ δέ.. 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 10.49 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; κινήσεων <b>from</b> movements, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 89e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; keep <b>silent</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.92, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 143 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 321: _plural_, τὰς ἡ. ἄγειν or ἔχειν, 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 3.114a, 11.493f. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__4.b</b></Level4> ἡσυχίαν ἔχειν, = {ἡ. ἄγειν}, but generally implying less continuance, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.45, 7.150, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.4.18, “HG” 3.2.27; ἡ. ἔχειν πρός τινα 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 28.7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; keep <b>silent</b>, τὰ δεινὰ ἡ. ἑκτέον <b>about</b> them, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th 